Step 1: Dataset Summary & Exploration¶

The pickled data is a dictionary with 4 key/value pairs:

  • 'features' is a 4D array containing raw pixel data of the traffic sign images, (num examples, width, height, channels).
  • 'labels' is a 1D array containing the label/class id of the traffic sign. The file signnames.csv contains id -> name mappings for each id.
  • 'sizes' is a list containing tuples, (width, height) representing the original width and height the image.
  • 'coords' is a list containing tuples, (x1, y1, x2, y2) representing coordinates of a bounding box around the sign in the image. THESE COORDINATES ASSUME THE ORIGINAL IMAGE. THE PICKLED DATA CONTAINS RESIZED VERSIONS (32 by 32) OF THESE IMAGES

The dataset (both training and validation) is unbalanced with some labels having almost 10 times more data than the under-represented classes. However, this may be because some signs are seen more often in reality as well. The mean of the data shows a traffic sign in the middle, that gives an indication that most of the data is centred in the 32x32 image. What is surprising to me is the standard deviation towards the boundary of the image has low pixel values. I would have expected the background of traffic signs to be varying a lot across images and thus the variance to be high. This would have made the boundaries brighter. However, this may be a result of cropping the images to 32x32, that decreases the variance.

Pre-process the Data Set (normalization, grayscale, etc.)¶

Minimally, the image data should be normalized so that the data has mean zero and equal variance. For image data, (pixel - 128)/ 128 is a quick way to approximately normalize the data and can be used in this project.

Other pre-processing steps are optional. You can try different techniques to see if it improves performance.

from cv2 import getRotationMatrix2D, warpAffine, INTER_LINEAR, equalizeHist, cvtColor, createCLAHE, COLOR_BGR2YUV, filter2D

# Here we consider a number of preprocessing functions that can be applied to images, either to enhance them or augment
# the dataset

def hist_equalization(image):
    """
    This function returns the histogram equalized image
    Args:
        image
    Returns:
        image
    """
    image1 = np.copy(image)
    image1[:,:,0] = equalizeHist(image1[:,:,0])
    image1[:,:,1] = equalizeHist(image1[:,:,1])
    image1[:,:,2] = equalizeHist(image1[:,:,2])
    return image1

def rotate_and_scale_image(image, angle, scale):
    """
    Source:
    http://opencv-python-tutroals.readthedocs.io/en/latest/py_tutorials/py_imgproc/py_geometric_transformations
    /py_geometric_transformations.html
    
    This function takes rotates the image around the center, scales it up/down and returns the resulting image
    Args:
        image
        angle
        scale
    Returns:
        image
    """
    image_center = tuple(np.array(image.shape[1::-1]) / 2)
    rot_mat = getRotationMatrix2D(image_center, angle, scale)
    return(warpAffine(image, rot_mat, image.shape[1::-1], flags=INTER_LINEAR))

def rotate_and_scale_image_Helper(image):
    """
    Helper function for rotating and scaling an image. Generates random angle and scale values
    Args:
        image
    Returns:
        image
    """
    # generate random angle from 5 to 15 degrees
    angle = random.uniform(5,15)
    scaling = [0.9, 1.1]
    # randomly make those angles negative
    sign_angle = [-1, 1]
    angle *= sign_angle[random.randint(0,1)]
    # select one of the two scalings: 0.9, 1.1
    scale = scaling[random.randint(0,1)]
    return(rotate_and_scale_image(image, angle, scale))
    

def perturb_image(image):
    """
    Perturbs an image in x and y direction
    Args:
        image
    Returns:
        image
    """
    # perturb in x and y directions by 2 pixels 
    pixel = 2
    dx, dy = np.random.randint(-pixel,pixel,2)
    transform_matrix = np.float32([[1,0,dx],[0,1,dy]])
    return(warpAffine(image, transform_matrix, (image.shape[0], image.shape[1]), flags=INTER_LINEAR))

def CLAHE(image):
    """
    Source: https://docs.opencv.org/3.1.0/d5/daf/tutorial_py_histogram_equalization.html
    Applies Contrast Limited Adaptive Histogram Equalization (CLAHE) on an image
    Args:
        image
    Returns:
        image
    """
    clahe = createCLAHE(tileGridSize=(4,4))
    image = clahe.apply(image)
    image = image.reshape(image.shape + (1,))
    return image
    
def grayscale(image):
    """
    Returns a grayscale image
    Args:
        image
    Returns:
        image
    """
    return(cvtColor(image, (COLOR_BGR2YUV))[:,:,0])

def motion_blur(image):
    """
    Source: https://www.packtpub.com/mapt/book/application_development/9781785283932/2/ch02lvl1sec21/motion-blur
    Blurs an image to represent image captured while in motion
    Args:
        image
    Returns:
        image
    """
    size = 2
    # generating the kernel
    kernel_motion_blur = np.zeros((size, size))
    kernel_motion_blur[int((size-1)/2), :] = np.ones(size)
    kernel_motion_blur = kernel_motion_blur / size

    # applying the kernel to the input image
    image = filter2D(image, -1, kernel_motion_blur)
    return(filter2D(image, -1, kernel_motion_blur))

print("From Left to right: Original Img, Histogram Equalization, CLAHE applied to YUV, Rotate by 15 degrees, Scale up 10%, Randomly perturb [+/-] 2 pixels, motion blur")

From Left to right: Original Img, Histogram Equalization, CLAHE applied to YUV, Rotate by 15 degrees, Scale up 10%, Randomly perturb [+/-] 2 pixels, motion blur

Both the equalizations: histogram equalization and CLAHE really enhance the images by improving the contrast. CLAHE works a little better by considering local equalization as compared to global equalization in histogram equalization. All subsequent processing is done on CLAHE processed images. Note that we consider grayscale images here inspired by http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/publis/pdf/sermanet-ijcnn-11.pdf

def data_augmentation(X_train, y_train):
    """
    This function creates a bigger training set by adding data augmentation. The output includes the following:
    1. original data set
    2. each image is rotated randomly by -15<angle<-5 or 5<angle<15 and scaled by 0.9 or 1.1
    3. Random perturbation of +/- 2 pixels
    4. Motion blurred by a kernel of size 4
    This provides a training set that is 4 times the original dataset
    Args:
        X_train
        y_train
    Returns:
        Augmented X_train
        Augmented y_train
    """
    # X_hist_eq = np.array([hist_equalization(image) for image in X_train])
    n_train = X_train.shape[0]
    X_rotate_and_scale = np.array([rotate_and_scale_image_Helper(image) for image in X_train]).reshape((n_train,32,32,1))
    X_perturb = np.array([perturb_image(image) for image in X_train]).reshape((n_train,32,32,1))
    X_motion_blur = np.array([motion_blur(image) for image in X_train]).reshape((n_train,32,32,1))
    X_train = np.concatenate((X_train, X_rotate_and_scale, X_perturb, X_motion_blur), axis = 0)
    y_train = np.concatenate((y_train, y_train, y_train, y_train))
    return X_train, y_train

def preprocess(image):
    """
    This funciton centers each image around zero and normalizes it with the standard deviation
    """
    return (image - mean)/std

# All data is preprocessed with grayscaling followed by CLAHE
X_train = np.array([CLAHE(grayscale(image)) for image in X_train])
X_valid = np.array([CLAHE(grayscale(image)) for image in X_valid])
X_test = np.array([CLAHE(grayscale(image)) for image in X_test])

# Data augmentation
X_train, y_train = data_augmentation(X_train, y_train)
mean = np.mean(X_train)
std = np.std(X_train)

# Centering around training set mean and normalized with training set standard deviation
X_train = np.array([preprocess(image) for image in X_train])
X_valid = np.array([preprocess(image) for image in X_valid])
X_test = np.array([preprocess(image) for image in X_test])
print("New number of training examples = ", X_train.shape)
print("Saving preprocessed images to avoid running re-running this module")
np.save('X_train', X_train)
np.save('X_valid', X_valid)
np.save('X_test', X_test)

A larger dataset (4 times) is generated from the training dataset by data augmentation. Each image is grayscaled and passed through CLAHE for equalization. Additionally, the images are centred around the training dataset mean and normalized with the standard deviation.

### Main 
from tensorflow.contrib.layers import flatten, batch_norm

def conv2d(x, W, b, strides=1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl=1, training = True):
    """
    Function applies the tensorflow convolution layer - includes 2D convolution, adds a bias, performs batch
    normalization, applies a ReLU activation function and implements dropout
    Args:
        x: input image
        W: weights
        b: bias
        strides: convolution operation stride
        padding_type: padding for convolution operation
        keep_prob_cl: keep probability for implementing dropout
        training: bool for batch norm, True when training, False otherwise
    Returns:
        tensorflow convolutional layer output
    """
    x = tf.nn.conv2d(x, W, strides=[1, strides, strides, 1], padding=padding_type)
    x = tf.nn.bias_add(x, b)
    x = batch_norm(x, is_training = training)
    x = tf.nn.relu(x) 
    return tf.nn.dropout(x, keep_prob_cl)

def maxpool2d(x, k=2, padding_type='VALID'):
    """
    Function applies maxpooling
    Args:
        x: input image
        k: stride length for pooling
        keep_prob_cl: keep probability for implementing dropout
    Returns:
        tensorflow maxpooling output
    """
    return tf.nn.max_pool(
        x,
        ksize=[1, k, k, 1],
        strides=[1, k, k, 1],
        padding = padding_type)

# this function implements the LeNet architecture
def LeNet(x, keep_prob_cl, keep_prob_fc, training):
    """
    Function implements LeNet
    Args:
        x: tensorflow input image
        keep_prob_cl:mtensorflow variable keep probability for implementing conv layer dropout
        keep_prob_fc: tensorflow variable keep probability for implementing fully connected layer dropout
        training: bool for batch norm, True when training, False otherwise
    Returns:
        LeNet arch output
    """
    weights = {
        'convNet1': tf.get_variable("convNet1", shape = [5, 5, 3, 6], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'convNet2': tf.get_variable("convNet2", shape = [5, 5, 6, 16], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'fc1': tf.get_variable("fc1", shape = [400, 120], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'fc2': tf.get_variable("fc2", shape = [120, 84], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'fc3': tf.get_variable("fc3", shape = [84, n_classes], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer())}

    biases = {
        'convNet1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([depth['convNet1']])),
        'convNet2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([depth['convNet2']])),
        'fc1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([depth['fc1']])),
        'fc2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([depth['fc2']])),
        'fc3': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_classes]))}
    
    # Layer 1 - 32*32*3 to 28*28*6
    conv1 = conv2d(x, weights['convNet1'], biases['convNet1'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    # Pooling - 28*28*6  to 14*14*6
    conv1 = maxpool2d(conv1, k=2, padding_type='VALID')

    # Layer 2 - 14*14*32 to 10*10*16
    conv2 = conv2d(conv1, weights['convNet2'], biases['convNet2'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    # Pooling - 10*10*16. Output = 5*5*16.
    conv2 = maxpool2d(conv2, k=2, padding_type='VALID')
    
    # Flatten - 5*5*16 to 400
    flat = flatten(conv2)

    # Fully connected layer - 400 to 120
    fc1 = tf.add(tf.matmul(flat, weights['fc1']), biases['fc1'])
    fc1 = tf.nn.relu(fc1)
    fc1 = tf.nn.dropout(fc1, keep_prob_fc)
    
    # Fully connected layer - 120 to 84
    fc2 = tf.add(tf.matmul(fc1, weights['fc2']), biases['fc2'])
    fc2 = tf.nn.relu(fc2)
    fc2 = tf.nn.dropout(fc2, keep_prob_fc)
    
    # Fully connected layer - 84 to n_classes
    logits = tf.add(tf.matmul(fc2, weights['fc3']), biases['fc3'])
    
    return logits

# Implements a flavor of http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/publis/pdf/sermanet-ijcnn-11.pdf
def SermaNet(x, keep_prob_cl, keep_prob_fc, training):
    """
    Function implements LeNet
    Args:
        x: tensorflow input image
        keep_prob_cl:mtensorflow variable keep probability for implementing conv layer dropout
        keep_prob_fc: tensorflow variable keep probability for implementing fully connected layer dropout
        training: bool for batch norm, True when training, False otherwise
    Returns:
        LeNet arch output
    """
    weights = {
        'convNet1': tf.get_variable("W1", shape = [5, 5, 3, 6], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'convNet2': tf.get_variable("W2", shape = [5, 5, 6, 16], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'convNet3': tf.get_variable("W3", shape = [5, 5, 16, 400], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'fc1': tf.get_variable("W4", shape = [1576, n_classes], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer())}

    biases = {
        'convNet1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([6])),
        'convNet2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([16])),
        'convNet3': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([400])),
        'fc1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_classes]))}
    
    # Layer 1 - 32*32*3 to 28*28*6
    conv1 = conv2d(x, weights['convNet1'], biases['convNet1'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    # Pooling - 28*28*6  to 14*14*6
    conv1 = maxpool2d(conv1, k=2, padding_type='VALID')

    # Layer 2 - 14*14*32 to 10*10*16
    conv2 = conv2d(conv1, weights['convNet2'], biases['convNet2'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    # Pooling - 10*10*16. Output = 5*5*16.
    conv2 = maxpool2d(conv2, k=2, padding_type='VALID')
    
    # Flatten - 14*14*6 to 1176
    flat = flatten(conv1)
    # Layer 3 convolution - 5*5*16 to 1*1*400
    conv3 = conv2d(conv2, weights['convNet3'], biases['convNet3'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    
    # Concat flat and conv3 - 1176 + 400 = 1576
    concat = tf.concat_v2([flat, flatten(conv3)], 1)
    concat = tf.nn.dropout(concat, keep_prob_fc)

    # Fully connected layer - 1576 to 43
    logits = tf.add(tf.matmul(concat, weights['fc1']), biases['fc1'])
    
    return logits

# Implements http://yann.lecun.com/exdb/publis/pdf/sermanet-ijcnn-11.pdf with lower filter widths
# this is final used architecture
def SermaNet2(x, keep_prob_cl, keep_prob_fc, training):
    """
    Function implements LeNet
    Args:
        x: tensorflow input image
        keep_prob_cl:mtensorflow variable keep probability for implementing conv layer dropout
        keep_prob_fc: tensorflow variable keep probability for implementing fully connected layer dropout
        training: bool for batch norm, True when training, False otherwise
    Returns:
        LeNet arch output
    """
    weights = {
        'convNet1': tf.get_variable("W1", shape = [5, 5, 1, 12], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'convNet2': tf.get_variable("W2", shape = [5, 5, 12, 32], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'fc1': tf.get_variable("W3", shape = [1388, 100], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer()),
        'fc2': tf.get_variable("W4", shape = [100, n_classes], initializer=tf.contrib.layers.xavier_initializer())}

    biases = {
        'convNet1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([12])),
        'convNet2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([32])),
        'fc1': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([100])),
        'fc2': tf.Variable(tf.zeros([n_classes]))}
    
    # Layer 1 - 32*32*3 to 28*28*12
    conv1 = conv2d(x, weights['convNet1'], biases['convNet1'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    # Pooling - 28*28*12  to 14*14*12
    conv1 = maxpool2d(conv1, k=2, padding_type='VALID')

    # Layer 2 - 14*14*12 to 10*10*32
    conv2 = conv2d(conv1, weights['convNet2'], biases['convNet2'], strides = 1, padding_type='VALID', keep_prob_cl = keep_prob_cl, training=training)
    # Pooling - 10*10*32. Output = 5*5*32.
    conv2 = maxpool2d(conv2, k=2, padding_type='VALID')
    
    # Maxpool - 14*14*12 to 7*7*12
    maxpool_layer1 = maxpool2d(conv1, k=2, padding_type='VALID')
    # Flatten 1st layer - 7*7*12 to 588
    flat_layer1 = flatten(maxpool_layer1)
    # Flatten 2nd layer 5*5*32 to 800
    flat_layer2 = flatten(conv2)
    
    # Concat the output of last two layers - 588 + 800 = 1388
    concat = tf.concat_v2([flat_layer1, flat_layer2], 1)
    concat = tf.nn.dropout(concat, keep_prob_cl)
    
    # Fully connected layer - 1388 to 100
    fc1 = tf.add(tf.matmul(concat, weights['fc1']), biases['fc1'])
    fc1 = batch_norm(fc1, is_training = training)
    fc1 = tf.nn.relu(fc1)
    fc1 = tf.nn.dropout(fc1, keep_prob_fc)
    
    # Fully connected layer - 84 to n_classes
    logits = tf.add(tf.matmul(fc1, weights['fc2']), biases['fc2'])
    
    return logits

A validation set can be used to assess how well the model is performing. A low accuracy on the training and validation sets imply underfitting. A high accuracy on the training set but low accuracy on the validation set implies overfitting.

# Model evaluation
correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(logits, 1), tf.argmax(one_hot_y, 1))
accuracy_operation = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, tf.float32))
saver = tf.train.Saver()

def evaluate(X_data, y_data):
    num_examples = len(X_data)
    total_accuracy = 0
    sess = tf.get_default_session()
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
        batch_x, batch_y = X_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE], y_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE]
        accuracy = sess.run(accuracy_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y, keep_prob_cl: 1.0, \
                                                           keep_prob_fc: 1, rate: learning_rate, training: False})
        total_accuracy += (accuracy * len(batch_x))
    return total_accuracy / num_examples

from sklearn import metrics
import seaborn as sn
import itertools

# Plotting the confusion matrix to analyze performance

def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    """
    Source: http://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_confusion_matrix.html
    This function prints and plots the confusion matrix.
    Normalization can be applied by setting `normalize=True`.
    """
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        print("Normalized confusion matrix")
    else:
        print('Confusion matrix, without normalization')

    # print(cm)
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    # plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
     
cm = metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_prediction)
plot_confusion_matrix(cm, sign_names['ClassId'].values)

Output Top 5 Softmax Probabilities For Each Image Found on the Web¶

For each of the new images, print out the model's softmax probabilities to show the certainty of the model's predictions (limit the output to the top 5 probabilities for each image). tf.nn.top_k could prove helpful here.

The example below demonstrates how tf.nn.top_k can be used to find the top k predictions for each image.

tf.nn.top_k will return the values and indices (class ids) of the top k predictions. So if k=3, for each sign, it'll return the 3 largest probabilities (out of a possible 43) and the correspoding class ids.

Take this numpy array as an example. The values in the array represent predictions. The array contains softmax probabilities for five candidate images with six possible classes. tf.nn.top_k is used to choose the three classes with the highest probability:

Step 4 (Optional): Visualize the Neural Network's State with Test Images¶

This Section is not required to complete but acts as an additional excersise for understaning the output of a neural network's weights. While neural networks can be a great learning device they are often referred to as a black box. We can understand what the weights of a neural network look like better by plotting their feature maps. After successfully training your neural network you can see what it's feature maps look like by plotting the output of the network's weight layers in response to a test stimuli image. From these plotted feature maps, it's possible to see what characteristics of an image the network finds interesting. For a sign, maybe the inner network feature maps react with high activation to the sign's boundary outline or to the contrast in the sign's painted symbol.

Provided for you below is the function code that allows you to get the visualization output of any tensorflow weight layer you want. The inputs to the function should be a stimuli image, one used during training or a new one you provided, and then the tensorflow variable name that represents the layer's state during the training process, for instance if you wanted to see what the LeNet lab's feature maps looked like for it's second convolutional layer you could enter conv2 as the tf_activation variable.

For an example of what feature map outputs look like, check out NVIDIA's results in their paper End-to-End Deep Learning for Self-Driving Cars in the section Visualization of internal CNN State. NVIDIA was able to show that their network's inner weights had high activations to road boundary lines by comparing feature maps from an image with a clear path to one without. Try experimenting with a similar test to show that your trained network's weights are looking for interesting features, whether it's looking at differences in feature maps from images with or without a sign, or even what feature maps look like in a trained network vs a completely untrained one on the same sign image.

In [36]:
### Visualize your network's feature maps here.
### Feel free to use as many code cells as needed.

# image_input: the test image being fed into the network to produce the feature maps
# tf_activation: should be a tf variable name used during your training procedure that represents the calculated state of a specific weight layer
# activation_min/max: can be used to view the activation contrast in more detail, by default matplot sets min and max to the actual min and max values of the output
# plt_num: used to plot out multiple different weight feature map sets on the same block, just extend the plt number for each new feature map entry

def outputFeatureMap(image_input, tf_activation, activation_min=-1, activation_max=-1 ,plt_num=1):
    # Here make sure to preprocess your image_input in a way your network expects
    # with size, normalization, ect if needed
    # image_input =
    # Note: x should be the same name as your network's tensorflow data placeholder variable
    # If you get an error tf_activation is not defined it may be having trouble accessing the variable from inside a function
    activation = tf_activation.eval(session=sess,feed_dict={x : image_input})
    featuremaps = activation.shape[3]
    plt.figure(plt_num, figsize=(15,15))
    for featuremap in range(featuremaps):
        plt.subplot(6,8, featuremap+1) # sets the number of feature maps to show on each row and column
        plt.title('FeatureMap ' + str(featuremap)) # displays the feature map number
        if activation_min != -1 & activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmin =activation_min, vmax=activation_max, cmap="gray")
        elif activation_max != -1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmax=activation_max, cmap="gray")
        elif activation_min !=-1:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", vmin=activation_min, cmap="gray")
        else:
            plt.imshow(activation[0,:,:, featuremap], interpolation="nearest", cmap="gray")
